//
// unfortunately there are infinitely many trees. we need all inputs AT ONCE.

// the idea: hand f ONE made-up input — a hypothesis, a tagged pair promising "some A"

// and it works! ...for functions that ignore their argument:

// but the simplest function there is fails the exam:

// we need to somehow make sure that all types check for a hypothesis first, before checking concretely: make a wrapper!

// Note: The following bits are AI-written, I haven't vetted them yet!

// the promise is ordinary data: anything can triage it apart, read it, or forge one
// so a function can DETECT the exam — real bools are leaf/stem, the promise is a fork:

// and functions that inspect their argument are never really examined:

// no encoding escapes this: checker and checked code play by the same five rules.
// the kernel's answer: stop running f. interpret its tree ONE APPLICATION AT A TIME,
// refusing any step that smashes, reads, or forges a promise — the walker.
// refusal means verdicts need a third value:

// a REAL hypothesis is a frozen call, wait(hyp_step)(meta) — applying it fires hyp_step instead of smashing it
// a frozen call stores its payload two rights down, and its left branch is a constant SIGNATURE:

// what does applying a promise mean? ask its TYPE: the meta's first slot says where applications land
// so a promised function applied to x re-freezes at the codomain, remembering x — a stuck call, a NEUTRAL

// a non-function type stores t there: misuse degrades to a promise of t, refused by everyone (a free InvalidType)

// one more scout: did a promise leak into a result?

// ─── the walker ───

// walk f x: the five rules by hand — building AROUND a promise is fine, taking one APART is refused
// two sanctioned exceptions: tree_eq (compares, nothing escapes) and the identity (rebuilds its fork)

// forging is caught mid-build:

// ─── real hypothesis walking ───

// rebuild the H-rule types on this machinery: meta = (where-applications-land, recognizer-body)

// the honest function type: mint a fresh promise of A, walk f on it, check B, demand no leaks
// (a claim about an ARBITRARY input can't mention the input)

// the payoff, higher-order: (g true) re-freezes at the codomain, and the H-rule accepts the stuck call

// mint + walk + occurs-check = ∀-introduction, the kernel's second trusted op: bind_hyp

// ─── the real kernel from here ───

// this file is lib/kernel/engine.disp in miniature:
//   promise / hyp_step   -> make_hyp / hyp_reduce (the meta slot holds a PROGRAM there: the respond)
//   walk                 -> param_walker / param_apply, same carve-out list
//   rec_wrap / make_type -> recognizer_wrap / make_recognizer, the same H-rule
//   forall               -> bind_hyp, the second trusted operation
//   ok / err / bind_ok   -> Ok / Err / bind (CheckerResult)
//   sig_of / is_promise  -> checker_sig / is_neutral (O(1) by hash-consing)
// there `not` and `double` aren't dead ends: types carry elimination protocols in their respond.
// records, equality, dependent codomains, and Type itself are the same ingredients: frozen calls, signatures, one walker.
